        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41648",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "What code do you execute, what is the expected outcome?\r\n\r\nPlease also attach a stack trace, and please note that it is encouraged to use absolute paths in your include path.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T05:43:53.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T05:46:35.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41649",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Its happening when simply trying to send a mail. What would be the easiest way for me to get the stack trace for the issue?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T06:05:23.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T06:05:23.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41651",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Would this be of any help. I ran a backtrace just above the line where the error was triggered:\r\n\r\n#0 Zend_Mail_Protocol_Abstract->_send(QUIT) called at [D:\\www\\libraries\\Zend\\Mail\\Protocol\\Smtp.php:385]\r\n#1 Zend_Mail_Protocol_Smtp->quit() called at [D:\\www\\libraries\\Zend\\Mail\\Transport\\Smtp.php:144]\r\n#2 Zend_Mail_Transport_Smtp->__destruct() ",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T06:59:59.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T06:59:59.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41652",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks, all that method basically does is call fclose(). Can you please check if this error also happens on linux?\r\n\r\nAnd as mentioned; it is suggested you use absolute paths in your include path rather than relative paths.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T07:58:17.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T07:58:17.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41653",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Yes, I ran the same script on our test server (which runs linux) and got the same result. It does send the email out though, it looks like where it goes wrong is when it tries to close the connection to the server?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T08:14:45.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T08:14:45.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41654",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Out of curiosity, why dont you use absolute paths?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T08:19:07.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T08:19:07.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41655",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "We have three seperate environments here - dev: which is basically the local PC, test: which is a closed off test-environment on our server, and production, which is the live environment. Because of this, the path is basically variable, defining it absolute would mean people having to edit it seperately for their own local environment (dev) and also changing it whenever the site goes on test or production environments. We use SVN to exchance it and sync it with our server, so conflicts would be lurking as well. Defining it relative saves all this hassle, and it doesnt matter where on the local filesystem we put the site. \r\n\r\nAlso it means we dont have to edit the paths for each individual site we produce.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T08:26:48.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T08:26:48.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41656",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I traced down the problem to the php manual:\r\n\r\n{quote}Note: Destructors called during the script shutdown have HTTP headers already sent. The working directory in the script shutdown phase can be different with some SAPIs (e.g. Apache).{quote} (http:\/\/php.net\/manual\/en\/language.oop5.decon.php)\r\n\r\nI will have to discuss this but I think it will be closed as wont-fix with the note to simply use absolute paths.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T08:26:54.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T08:26:54.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41657",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Frankly, that reason is bogus. You can dynamically determine the absolute path. As is shown in basically any ZF tutorial:\r\n{code}\/\/ Define path to application directory\r\ndefined('APPLICATION_PATH')\r\n    || define('APPLICATION_PATH', realpath(dirname(__FILE__) . '\/..\/application'));\r\n\r\n\/\/ Define application environment\r\ndefined('APPLICATION_ENV')\r\n    || define('APPLICATION_ENV', (getenv('APPLICATION_ENV') ? getenv('APPLICATION_ENV') : 'production'));\r\n\r\n\/\/ Ensure library\/ is on include_path\r\nset_include_path(implode(PATH_SEPARATOR, array(\r\n    realpath(APPLICATION_PATH . '\/..\/library'),\r\n    get_include_path(),\r\n)));{code}\r\n\r\nThat will dynamically set an absolute include path.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T08:29:31.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T08:29:31.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41658",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "So silly I didn't think of that, changing it to \r\n{noformat}$sLibraryPath = realpath(dirname(__FILE__).\"..\/..\/..\/libraries\");{\/noformat}\r\nSolved the issue.\r\n\r\nGuess the issue is more related to the PHP core rather then Zend itself anyway. Thanks for the help!",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freekazoid",
                        "name": "freekazoid",
                        "displayName": "Freek van Rijt",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-07-21T08:40:31.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-07-21T08:40:31.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/42337",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=afx114",
                        "name": "afx114",
                        "displayName": "jsnod",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I am having a similar issue, with a slight difference: PHP complains about an open_basedir restriction. Here is my error:\r\n\r\n{noformat}\r\nWarning:  require_once() [<a href='function.require-once'>function.require-once<\/a>]: open_basedir restriction in effect. File(Zend\/Mail\/Protocol\/Exception.php) is not within the allowed path(s): (\/home\/username\/:\/tmp\/:\/usr\/share\/pear\/:\/dev\/) in \/usr\/share\/pear\/ZendFramework-1.10.8-minimal\/library\/Zend\/Mail\/Protocol\/Abstract.php on line 295\r\nFatal error:  Can't load Zend\/Mail\/Protocol\/Exception.php, open_basedir restriction. in \/usr\/share\/pear\/ZendFramework-1.10.8-minimal\/library\/Zend\/Mail\/Protocol\/Abstract.php on line 295\r\n{noformat}\r\n\r\nThis is odd because my open_basedir value is set to: \r\n{noformat}php_admin_value open_basedir \"\/home\/username\/:\/tmp\/:\/usr\/share\/pear\/:\/dev\/\"{noformat}\r\n\r\nMy include paths are already absolute, and look like so:\r\n{noformat}\/home\/username\/library:\/home\/username\/application\/models:\/home\/username\/application\/models\/notifications:\/usr\/share\/pear\r\n{noformat}\r\n\r\nZF resides in \/usr\/share\/pear\/, so by all indications the file should be able to be found and require'd because it exists in the include_path and my include_path is allowed in open_basedir.  If I remove the open_basedir restriction it works as expected, however, I'd rather not do that for security reasons.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=afx114",
                        "name": "afx114",
                        "displayName": "jsnod",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-09-22T18:41:00.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-09-22T18:41:00.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/42364",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=afx114",
                        "name": "afx114",
                        "displayName": "jsnod",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "After doing additional tests\/research, you are right, this is an issue with PHP.  The current working directory changes to '\/' before object-destructors are called, which is why my open_basedir or throwing an error.\r\n\r\nhttp:\/\/bugs.php.net\/bug.php?id=31570\r\n\r\nNot sure if this is classified as a \"feature\" or a \"bug\" though.  :)",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=afx114",
                        "name": "afx114",
                        "displayName": "jsnod",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-09-24T12:40:23.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-09-24T12:40:23.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
    },
